12. Data collection procedures
RR TEAM INSTRUCTIONS: Please describe the process by which
you will collect your data. If you are using human subjects, this
should include how you will identify the population from which
you obtain subjects, recruitment efforts, payment for participation,
how subjects will be selected for eligibility from the initial pool
(e.g. inclusion and exclusion rules), and your study timeline, in
addition to the experimental/observational protocol itself. For
studies that don’t include human subjects, include information
about how you will collect samples, duration of data gathering
efforts, source or location of samples, or batch numbers you will
use.
Where details are described in other questions (e.g. study design,
blinding) you can refer to those questions, so long as the complete
description is provided somewhere. You are strongly encouraged to
supplement your description here with materials (which might
include stimuli, survey instruments, code for running data
collection software, instructions for experimenters) uploaded to
your OSF project, in the “Materials and Methods” component.
Please use the specific file names when referencing them in your
description.

Specific points to keep in mind (please also consult the Reviewer
Criteria):
Does the preregistration describe the target population, and how
members of the target population are sampled for the study?
Does the protocol describe in detail any materials that will be
presented to participants, including variation or structure in those
materials relevant to the experimental design? Are these materials
available for review?
We plan to recruit participants from a larger pool of healthy Polish
adults who will volunteer to take part in a study on moral
cognition. We plan to recruit up to 300 students (150 men, 150
women) in two phases: 160 people in the first phase and 140 in the
second phase (the second phase will be conducted if the results
obtained for the first phase differ from the original findings).
Participants will be recruited via announcements on local social and
job portals, as well as via websites of Krakow universities. The
study announcement will say that participants to take part in a
study on moral decisions among the Polish population are sought.
Participants need to be students who have not taken any advanced
psychology courses or have not been exposed to moral dilemma
literature. They will be told that participation in the study is
voluntary and will be compensated with a monetary reward of 30
PLN (equivalent to $7.7, the round amount in the local currency
which is closest to that paid in the original study). Those who
would like to participate will be asked to sign up for a selected
study slot in an online form using a nickname of their choosing (for
anonymity).
The data in the lab will be collected in four steps. First, participants
will report their current mood and the level of arousal on a 7-point
Likert scale (mood: 1=positive, 7=negative; arousal: 1=low,
7=high). Participants will then be seated alone in a cubicle and
asked to complete a pretest with 20 moral dilemmas. They will be
led to believe that it is a practice prior to the main task. In fact, the

pretest will measure individual participant's baseline moral decision
tendencies unaffected by experimental manipulation.
Second, they will be asked to perform the main task which consists
of responding to a series of 50 moral dilemmas: 20 personal-moral
dilemmas, 15 impersonal-moral dilemmas, and 15 nonmoral control
dilemmas. Crucially, the dilemmas will be solved under social
observation or not (the description of the manipulation can be
found in the Study Protocol document at https://osf.io/uyt9p/?
view_only=ca6e17c6f1844a4aab51ca749185308e).
Third, they will be asked to complete a lexical decision task (the
same as in the original study) and fourth, they will answer a set of
post-experiment questionnaires including measures of empathy
(Interpersonal Reactivity Index) (Davis, 1983), need for cognition
(NfC) (Cacioppo & Petty, 1982) and fear of negative evaluation
(Leary, 1983). Finally, participants' mood and arousal will be
measured again for comparing the subjective experiences of
physiological states before and after the task.
All materials used are the same as reported by Lee et al. (2018,
translated in Polish) and can be found at https://osf.io/6tf8n/?
view_only=ca6e17c6f1844a4aab51ca749185308e under Study
Protocol and Study Material (including all dilemmas, tasks, and
scales used).
