At the beginning and the end of the experiment participants’ mood
and level of arousal will be measured with one seven-point item for
each variable (see Study Materials: https://osf.io/2hkg7/?
view_only=ca6e17c6f1844a4aab51ca749185308e).
In the pre-test, participants’ moral decision will be measured with a
set of 20 moral dilemmas (participants will make binary decisions
on the appropriateness of the behaviors described at the end of the
scenarios and then will be prompted to indicate the level of
confidence for each decision on a 4-point Likert scale, ranging from
1- very inappropriate to 4 - very appropriate).
In the main task, participants will answer 50 moral dilemmas (of
three types; see manipulated variables) also giving binary choices
and then indicating the level of confidence on 1-4 scale (ranging
from very inappropriate to very appropriate).
In the lexical decision task, participants’ accuracy and reaction
times will be measured. Reaction times for accurate responses for
each word category (Reputation, Non-Reputation, Warmth,
Competence, and Non-word; see Study Protocol: https://osf.io/
vscu8/?view_only=ca6e17c6f1844a4aab51ca749185308e) will be
analyzed.

At the end of the experiment, participants’ empathy will be
measured with the Interpersonal Reactivity Index (Davis, 1983),
need for cognition with the Need for Cognition Scale (Cacioppo &
Petty, 1982) and the fear of negative evaluation with the Fear of
Negative Evaluation Scale (Leary, 1983).
18. Indices
RR TEAM INSTRUCTIONS: If any of the measured variables
described in Section 17 are going to be combined into a composite
measure (including simply a mean), describe what measures you
will use and how they will be combined. Include either a formula or
a precise description of your method. If you are using a more
complicated statistical method to combine measures (e.g. a factor
analysis), you can note that here but describe the exact method in
the analysis plan section.
Specific points to keep in mind (please also consult the Reviewer
Criteria):
Does the preregistration specify each of the composite measures
(e.g. mean scores, factor scores) that are needed for the focal
analysis, and which of the measured variables in Section 17 are
used in each one (e.g. the happiness, joy, and satisfaction items will
be used to create the ‘positive feelings’ measure)?
Does the preregistration provide a detailed description of the
methodology or a precise formula that will be used to construct
each composite measure?
Responses to the items of scales used (the Interpersonal Reactivity
Index, the Need for Cognition Scale and the Fear of Negative
Evaluation Scale) will be combined into general scores, so that one
score per each scale is obtained (i.e. responses for each scale will be
averaged, having recoded the reversely scored items).
To analyze data from the pretest moral dilemmas, parameters of
deontological moral judgements (D) and utilitarian moral

judgements (U) will be computed based on the process dissociation
analysis (Conway & Gawronski, 2013). Specifically, for each
participant, we will calculate the probability of rejecting harm in
congruent and incongruent dilemmas separately (numbers of
choosing the answer “inappropriate” divided by a number of made
choices). Utilitarian parameter will be calculated by subtracting the
probability of rejecting harm in incongruent dilemmas from the
probability of rejecting harm in congruent dilemmas. The
deontological parameter will be calculated by subtracting the U-
parameter from 1 and dividing the probability of rejecting harm in
incongruent dilemmas by this difference score.
For the main task, we will compute the proportion of deontological
decisions (rejecting harm) to all decisions made, separately for each
type of dilemmas, as well as for all dilemmas combined.
As for the decision confidence, all raw rating scores will be
converted into the values between 1 and 2 so that the higher
number indicates stronger decision confidence for both types of
moral
judgements. Next, we will compute mean confidence for each
dilemma type, as well as for all dilemmas combined.
Reaction times will be averaged for each dilemma type respectively,
as well as for all dilemmas combined.
For Lexical Decision Task, we will average RTs of the correct trials,
separately for each word category (reputation vs. control vs.
warmth vs. competence).
Analysis Plan
19. Statistical models
RR TEAM INSTRUCTIONS: This section should describe in detail
the analysis that will be performed to replicate the focal result. This

analysis must align as closely as possible with the original study’s
analysis, even if you have identified limitations in the original
study. The level of detail should allow anyone to reproduce your
analyses from your description below. Examples of what should be
specified: the model; each variable; adjustments made to the
standard errors and to case weighting; additional analyses that are
required to set up the focal analysis ; the software used.
Beyond the replication of the focal analysis from the original study,
it is at your discretion to test the claim using other analytic
approaches as a check of the robustness of the claim. The original
test should be listed first and be clearly distinguished from any
other tests. If you are testing additional confirmatory hypotheses,
describe them in the same order as you numbered them in the
“Hypotheses” section above and make clear reference to the specific
hypothesis being tested for each.
Specific points to keep in mind (please also consult the Reviewer
Criteria):
Does the preregistration specify which statistical model will be used
to provide the ‘focal evidence’ for the SCORE test (e.g. a regression
coefficient in a larger multiple regression model), and does it
correspond closely to the model and evidence from the original
study?
Does the preregistration describe each variable that will be included
in the focal analysis, and what role each variable has (e.g.
dependent variable, independent variable)?
Does the preregistration include a detailed specification of the focal
analysis, including interactions, lagged terms, controls, etc.?
For the purposes of SCORE, to test H* in line with the original
paper, we will run a 2 × 3 mixed ANOVA on the proportion of
deontological responses made by each individual. The model will
include group (observed vs. control) as a between-subjects factor

and the dilemma type (personal vs. impersonal vs. nonmoral) as a
within-subjects factor.
Additionally, to test hypothesis 2, we will analyze decision
confidence and reaction times. We will thus run a 2 × 3 × 2 mixed
ANOVA on participants' ratings on decision confidence. The analysis
will involve group (observed vs. control) as a between-subjects
factor, and dilemma type (personal vs. impersonal vs. non-moral)
and response type (appropriate vs. inappropriate) as within-subjects
factors. For reaction times, a 2 × 3 × 2 mixed ANOVA with the
same factors will be applied.
Data from the lexical decision task will also be analyzed. Average
RTs of the correct trials will be analyzed in a 2 × 4 mixed ANOVA
with the group (observed vs. control) as a between-subject factor,
and the word category (reputation vs. control vs. warmth vs.
competence) as a within-subjects factor.
Additionally, as in the original paper, we will check for any
potential differences in the pre-test. To that aim, we will run a 2×2
mixed ANOVA on the standardized D and U parameters to test the
interaction between the group (observed vs. control) and the
parameter type (D vs. U).
To rule out any personality differences between the two groups, we
will run a series of independent sample t-tests on IRI, NfC and FNE
scores. The self-reported ratings on mood and arousal will also be
examined by a 2 (pre- vs. post) × 2 (group) mixed ANOVA to
analyze the potential impact of manipulation on participants'
subjective experience of psychological states.
As in the original paper, all statistical analyses will be carried out
using SPSS software (Statistical
Package for the Social Sciences, IBM Corp., Armonk, NY, USA) with
the type I error rate set to α = 0.05 (two-tailed). Greenhouse-
Geisser correction will be applied for violations of sphericity in the

analysis of variance involving repeated measures. Bonferroni-
corrected paired samples t-tests will be conducted to analyze the
simple effects for a statistically significant interaction. When
appropriate, Cohen's d and partial eta-squared will be reported as
effect size measures.
